definitions.definition: used with another verb to form questions and negative sentences, including negative orders, and sometimes in affirmative sentences for reasons of style:
used instead of the main verb in questions that are added to the end of a sentence to check information:
examples: You met him at our party, didn't you?

definitions.definition: used instead of the main verb in questions that are added to the end of a sentence as a way of expressing surprise:
examples: So Susannah and May finally got married, did they?

definitions.definition: to perform, take part in, or achieve something:
examples: That was a really stupid thing to do.

definitions.definition: to take action to deal with something:
examples: It's a global problem - what can individuals do about it?

definitions.definition: to treat someone well or badly

examples: There are no special privileges for the managers - we believe in fair dos all round (= equal treatment for everyone) in this company.

definitions.definition: the first note of the sol-fa musical scale:
examples: Would you sing me a do, please?
